<HEADLINE>
Zambia on high alert of bird flu outbreak
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 2 (Xinhua)
</P>
<P>
Zambia's National Taskforce on Avian Influenza (NTAI) has said it
had put in place necessary measure to forestall any possible
outbreak of the disease, commonly known as bird flu, in the
country.
</P>
<P>
NTAI chairperson Peter Mangani said here Wednesday the taskforce
has drawn up a budget of 12 million U.S. dollars for the creation
of the national capacity to respond to a possible outbreak of the
disease.
</P>
<P>
Mangani said a national response plan had also been worked out
with emphasis on public awareness, surveillance and development
of reliable diagnostic capacity in the prevention of the bird flu
outbreak in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said the taskforce which comprises ministries of agriculture,
health and information would remain alert in ensuring that the
disease would not spread to Zambia from other African nations
like Egypt and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has committed 1 million dollars while the European
Union through the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) has
also pledged 215,000 dollars to Zambia's efforts to strengthen
its capacity to respond to any outbreak of bird flu, according to
NTAI.
</P>
<P>
A total of 291 cases of bird flu has been reported worldwide
between 2003 and 2007 among human beings out of which 172 have
died, NTAI said.
</P>
